"{""m_segment_id"":1,""video_id"":1,""merged_name"":""En_1_001"",""start_time"":0,""end_time"":317.76000000000005,""merged_text"":""Hello learners, good day to all, I am Dr. Vishal Sooth, teacher educator. Today we are going to discuss about one of the most important aspect of teaching learning process that is continuous and comprehensive evaluation. Without this process, teaching learning process can never be termed as completed in itself. So, we will today discuss about different aspects of continuous and comprehensive evaluation and how this process is carried on in the classroom in the schools. So, the learners, the main points of today's discussion will be the holistic personality development, the evaluation for holistic development, meaning of evaluation and its importance, continuity in evaluation, the comprehensiveness in evaluation, evaluation of scholastic aspects and the evaluation of course scholastic aspects. So, our today's discussion will move around, will orient around these major aspects, these major points which are related to continuous and comprehensive evaluation in teaching learning process. Now, as you know that the educational process or teaching learning process is carried for the personality development and personality development has three major dimensions. Three major dimensions of the personality are the cognitive aspect of the personality, effective aspect of the personality and the third one is psychomotor aspect of the personality. So, we provide education to the students or the teaching learning process is carried for the development of these three aspects of personality, the cognitive aspect, the effective aspect and the psychomotor or which is related to the skill part of our personality. Now, holistic development of our personality can be seen in four major dimensions. First is related to intellectual development, which is related to the mental abilities, the development of mental abilities among students. These mental abilities include reasoning, these mental abilities include creative thinking, these mental abilities include critical thinking. So, these are the part of intellectual development, one of the dimension of holistic personality development, the other is physical development. Then the third dimension of our personality is emotions that we wish to develop the emotions, we wish to develop the emotional part of the personality of an individual and fourth aspect of individual personality is related to the social and moral development. That means through education, through teaching learning process we wish to develop social and moral values among the students. So, these are the parts, these are the aspects, these are the dimensions of our personality and we provide education to the children to for developing these four aspects of our personality. Now, if personality development is there, then definitely a question is there that there must be certain procedures for evaluating the holistic development of personality of any child. So, how to carry out this evaluation? But before that one question is why evaluation? Then what process is constitutive evaluation? Then the next question arises when to evaluate? Next question whether it should be a single shot event? The evaluation should be single shot event carried at one time only or it should be continual or a periodic press process carried on regularly. So, these are the question which we have to answer before implementation of any educational process or before assessing the personality of any child. Apart from this there are certain other questions which arise that what to evaluate, whether to evaluate all the dimensions of the personality of the individual and then the question arises how to evaluate, whether there is only single tool, single technique to evaluate or there are a number of tools, there are multi tools, there are multi techniques to evaluate the different aspects or different dimensions of the personality of an individual. So, in order to answer these queries, first question why evaluation? Why the need of evaluation is there? The first is to ascertain child's development in various dimensions at different stages. At different stages of development throughout his life if we wish to ascertain the child's development in different dimensions there is need of evaluation. Then the other need for evaluation is to certify the learners, to certify the students in terms of what has been achieved by that student and what is still missing, what he has not learned so far."",""audio_segment_path"":null,""video_segment_path"":""D:\\Video_Lecture\\English\\Derived\\merged_segment_5min\\1\\En_1_001.mp4""}"
"{""m_segment_id"":2,""video_id"":1,""merged_name"":""En_1_002"",""start_time"":318,""end_time"":663.5,""merged_text"":""So, for this evaluation is required. Then the third reason for conducting evaluation is to identify the learning difficulties of the child, whether the child has learned all the concepts that has been taught by the teacher in the class or not. If there are certain learning difficulties, if there are certain hard spots then those learning difficulties are to be identified through the process of evaluation. And then the next need for evaluation is, the next task of evaluation is that on the basis of evaluation we try to provide remediation. Remediation means corrective measures. We try to apply the corrective measures on the basis of the identification of the learning difficulties of the students. Then to ascertain the effectiveness of three M's, matter, methods and materials. That means whether the content matter taken for the teaching learning process was effective and if it was effective to what extent it was effective. To ascertain this thing we need evaluation. What methods have been adopted by the teacher in order to ascertain the effectiveness of those teaching learning methods, those pedagogical techniques we have to do evaluation. Then in order to ascertain the effectiveness of the materials, the teaching learning equipments or the teaching learning materials used by the teacher during the teaching learning process in order to ascertain the effectiveness of those materials, those equipments we need evaluation. Then the next reason for conducting evaluation is to grade a child as pass or fail or to promote him to the next class. So this all is done on the basis of evaluation and the last and foremost and important reason is to make evaluation as assessment of learning, assessment for learning, assessment as learning and assessment in learning. So assessment or evaluation should be there should be assessment of learning, assessment for learning for improving learning, assessment itself is a learning and assessment in learning. So these are the aspects for these reasons we conduct evaluation in the classroom processes, we conduct evaluation in our education so that the different dimensions of personality development could be assessed appropriately in an effective manner. So this was the need to conduct evaluation. Now what elements constitute evaluation? Evaluation consisted of two major aspects, two major elements one is measurement and the other is assessment. That means measurement and assessment both constitute evaluation plus value judgments. Value judgment regarding the child is also a part of evaluation. That means evaluation is very broader in nature is having a largest scope and measurement is a part of evaluation. Assessment is a part of evaluation plus value judgments. The value judgment means the judgment about the value of the child or when we remarks when we give remark to the child then that also become a part of evaluation. So evaluation is both measurement as well as assessment plus value judgment about the child. Then when to evaluate the next important question is when to evaluate the child's progress. Then the question is it should be at continual intervals, it should be at periodic intervals and it should be a regular process. The evaluation of the child should be a regular process and it should not be a single short event. It should not be conducted at only one time. Second thing about evaluation that it should be comprehensive in nature. Comprehensive means it should cover all the aspects of the personality, it should cover all the dimensions of personality. That means evaluation should be multi-dimensional in nature in which all the dimensions of the personality should be evaluated and that evaluation is known as comprehensive in itself. Now when we talk of continuous evaluation that it should be conducted at regular intervals, it should not be a single short event. Then when we talk of this continuous evaluation what do we mean by continuous evaluation? This is the question what do we mean by continuous evaluation? Continuous evaluation means that there is frequent conduct of unit testing. We try to conduct tests of the students, we try to evaluate the students at regular intervals, at frequent intervals. Then there is regularity of assessment. That means assessment is conducted on regular intervals. Then there is use of corrective measures. That means use of corrective measures means if a child is not able to learn something, child has certain hard spots, learning difficulties. Then through this continuous evaluation we try to provide him corrective measures, we try to provide him feedback."",""audio_segment_path"":null,""video_segment_path"":""D:\\Video_Lecture\\English\\Derived\\merged_segment_5min\\1\\En_1_002.mp4""}"
"{""m_segment_id"":3,""video_id"":1,""merged_name"":""En_1_003"",""start_time"":663.5,""end_time"":1241.54,""merged_text"":""Then there is provision of retesting. When the corrective measures applied are applied, when the feedback is given to the student about his or her difficulties, particular learning difficulties, then again those students are tested. In order to assess whether the students have learned those things or not or whether those learning difficulties still exist or not or have got removed. So in order to do that we again conduct the process of testing. So this process is known as retesting and it is also a part of continuous evaluation. Then if certain particular specific learning difficulties remain there, then we try to diagnose those learning gaps. We try to identify those learning gaps and it is also a part of continuous evaluation. So you can see on the screen that different features of continuous evaluation are there that the test unit tests are conducted at regular intervals. The assessment is carried out frequently. There is periodic assessment. Then there is provision of corrective measures and provision of feedback to the students regarding their learning difficulties. Then the provision of retesting is there where the students are again tested to know whether the learning difficulties have got removed or not and then if the particular hard spots are there, then on the basis of evaluation we also diagnose those learning gaps. So these are the characteristics of continuous evaluation. I hope you have understood about these features of continuous evaluation. Now continuous evaluation includes formative evaluation and second summative evaluation. Formative evaluation means what? Formative evaluation means the evaluation testing of the students carried out at short intervals on a regular basis that is known as formative evaluation. Formative evaluation, this word has been taken from the word formation. Now what? Formation of what? That means formation of the content matter, the formation of the knowledge during the teaching learning process and when the formation of that knowledge is going on in the classroom during the teaching learning process and then during that formation process we try to evaluate the students at regular intervals either through verbal means, verbal questioning or through written questioning then that sort of evaluation is known as formative evaluation. Now why we conduct such type of formative evaluation? This formative evaluation is done to identify the learning progress, to check the learning progress of the students and to identify the difficulties if any remains there. So formative evaluation is for improving the learning among the students. Then another part of continuous evaluation is summative evaluation. Summative evaluation as the word itself says summative means sum total. When the sum total of the learning experiences have been given to the students then at the end of the semester, at the end of the session, at the end of a particular course when we evaluate the students then that sort of evaluation is known as summative evaluation. Summative evaluation includes all the content matter, all the syllabi of a particular course. It is generally conducted at the end of the session and the main purpose of summative evaluation is to grade or to certify the learner as pass or fail or to promote the student from one class to the other class. So there are differences between these two parts that is formative evaluation and summative evaluation. Formative evaluation is for improving learning, for identifying learning difficulties to provide feedback to the students whereas summative evaluation is done to grade the student as pass or fail or to certify that learner or to promote that learner from first class to the other class. But both of these formative as well as summative evaluation these are the part of continuous evaluation. So this in CCE the continuous aspect of evaluation indicates two. One the formative evaluation or the summative and the second summative evaluation. Now the comprehensive evaluation. Comprehensive as we already said that comprehensive evaluation means the evaluation of all the aspects of our personality that means cognitive aspect, affective aspect as well as psychomotor aspect. So when all the aspects of child's personality are evaluated through different means then we say that such sort of evaluation is known as comprehensive in nature. Comprehensive which covers all the aspects different aspects of child's personality and in school situations these aspects can be classified into two parts. One are the scholastic aspects of child personality the other are co-scholastic aspects of the child personality. Now what these scholastic and co-scholastic aspects of child personality indicates or refer to? Now as you know that we have different abilities. Any child any individual have different abilities and these abilities can be classified into six parts as given by the balloons taxonomy of cognitive domain. Now these abilities include the knowledge among the children, the understanding level among the children, the ability to apply different concepts in different situation that is also a part of our cognitive aspect of our personality. Then there is analytical abilities among the students then there are evaluating abilities or synthesis abilities among the students and then creative abilities among the students. So our personality that cognitive dimension of our personality is comprised of different abilities which you can see on the screen which includes knowledge, understanding, application abilities, analytical abilities, evaluation abilities and creative abilities. Now these are the parts of scholastic aspects. Now when we talk of scholastic aspects, scholastic aspects means those aspects which are related to the particular subjects in the school. These subjects may be mathematics, may be science, may be social science, may be languages. Now your social sciences or any other subjects but when we talk of these subjects why these subjects are taught in the school? The main reason for teaching these subjects in the school that is to develop different abilities among the students. Now what those abilities are? We have already discussed these abilities are to develop the knowledge among the students, to develop their understanding abilities regarding different concepts which are covered in mathematics, science, social science, language or other subjects. So that means different abilities whether analytical abilities or knowledge abilities or understanding abilities or creative abilities. So these abilities are developed through different subjects which are taught in the class. So in order to assess whether these abilities have been developed among the students or not for that we conduct evaluation and that evaluation should be conducted at regular intervals, at frequent intervals and that is why it is required what a teacher should do in the class. Teach a small part of the unit, evaluate the students, find their learning mistakes. If any errors are there, any difficulties are there, provide them feedback, provide them remediation, provide them corrective measures then retest whether those learning difficulties have got removed or not and then move to the next part of that unit, next lesson of that unit. So in this way the teacher can move or teacher can improve the learning among the students and provide them feedback at regular intervals. So this sort of evaluation which is carried out in different subjects at regular intervals by the teacher to improve the learning that is evaluation in scholastic aspects and how this evaluation is carried out either through oral questioning or through written questions or through practical works. So different techniques are there to evaluate whether the student have learned or not. In order to do that teacher may apply any of the technique."",""audio_segment_path"":null,""video_segment_path"":""D:\\Video_Lecture\\English\\Derived\\merged_segment_5min\\1\\En_1_003.mp4""}"
"{""m_segment_id"":4,""video_id"":1,""merged_name"":""En_1_004"",""start_time"":1241.54,""end_time"":1541.7,""merged_text"":""It should be through observation, it should be through small classroom test, it should be through evaluation after one month or evaluation after three months but it should be a regular feature and the scholastic part or the part which is related to different subjects of study in the school that is known as evaluation of scholastic aspect and at regular intervals. So this is a part of comprehensive, one part of comprehensive evaluation. Now the other part of comprehensiveness is the evaluation of the scholastic aspects. Now scholastic aspects these are related to child's personality. This is also one part of the child's personality which are related to scholastic aspect. We organize, as you know we organize different activities in the school, co-curricular activities or co-academic activities, other activities out of school activities are organized by the teachers and the school authorities. Now why these activities are organized in the schools? This is done so that the different aspects of child's personality could be groomed to the highest level, could be developed to the maximum extent possible so that we organize different type of these activities in the school. Now what these activities, what type of activities are organized in the school? First as you can see on the screen we try to provide them ICT training. ICT training means the training in information and communication technology. We try to develop them among them the attitude and values. We try to develop among the children the life skills. We try to provide them health and physical education. We try to develop among them the scientific skills through different practicals or through different field based activities. We try to develop among them different values related to dignity of the labor, dignity of the manual labor for this work education or SUPW related activities are organized in the schools. Then there is provision of performing and visual arts to develop among them the creative talent in the students. Then literary and creative skills are developed through different cultural activities. Different sports activities are organized for the better physical development of the children and in order to develop among them organizational and leadership skills we frame different committees, we frame we constitute different clubs in the schools so that such type of leadership skills and organizational skills could be developed among the students. So these are the cost-quality aspects which are related to child's personality. Now in order to assess, in order to evaluate whether the child is developing in a proper manner in terms of his physical aspect or not, whether appropriate leadership or organizational skills are being developed among the students or followers skills are developed among the students, in order to evaluate these we have different techniques a teacher can adopt those different techniques to evaluate whether these parts of the personality, these cost-cholastic aspects have been developed to the maximum extent possible or not. So that means comprehensiveness means evaluation in all sort of activities which are undertaken in the school. Earlier what was done before implementation of CC in the schools only the evaluation of the students was done in the cost-cholastic aspect only the achievement of the students was assessed in different subjects of study that is how much a child has got in mathematics, how many marks a child has received in science subjects. So this was earlier the major emphasis of the educational process but in continuous and comprehensive evaluation what we try to evaluate is that is a child should not only be evaluated in subjects of study in theory subjects but rather he should be evaluated in all the activities, all the parts of different school activities which include life skills, his development of attitude and values, development of physical aspect of the personality, development of scientific skills or work education skills."",""audio_segment_path"":null,""video_segment_path"":""D:\\Video_Lecture\\English\\Derived\\merged_segment_5min\\1\\En_1_004.mp4""}"
